{
  "doc_id": "16284",
  "text": "On a more fundamental level, how new functional properties evolve in the RdRPs (and in other protein families for that matter) is poorly understood. Gene duplication followed by paralog divergence is a major driving force in protein evolution [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and it clearly contributed to RdRP diversification. Indeed, many species encode more than one distinct RdRP, with three paralogous genes present in N. crassa (QDE-1, SAD-1, and RRP-3), four in C. elegans, and six in Arabidopsis [CITATION_3] . The last eukaryotic common ancestor might have contained three functionally distinct RdRPs giving rise to the ␣, ␤, and ␥ branches of the RdRP genealogy, an arrangement that was further modified by lineage-specific gene duplications and losses [CITATION_4] .",
